\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qc\ul\f0\fs40\lang2057 When can we really ignore external forces in projectile motion problems?\fs25\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\ulnone\b\fs24 Introduction\par
\b0 When we attempt to analyse anything in physics, we must start with a model for the scenario at hand. How accurate and refined this model is depends on the desired reliability of the results. Some things are straightforward to include in these models, such as weights and inclines, while other influences are more laborious to implement. Up until now, we have been allowed to assume things like friction and air resistance are simply 'negligible', but exactly how justified are we in making these assumptions?\par
\b Why simplify our models?\b0\par
To create a model is to reduce a situation to its most basic form: removing all unnecessary details from a problem while pinning down exactly what the key factors affecting the system are. Let's consider a very simple problem from projectile motion: suppose we have a ball, and it is dropped from a bridge 100 m above the ground. How long does the ball take to hit the ground?\par
Using our traditional methods, we can quickly get the answer to be\par
