But think about all the assumptions we have implicitly made while doing this calculation:\par

\pard{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf2\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1 Ball has no size: implies no air resistance, no upthrust, modelled as a particle\par
{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}Ball does not rotate; implies no Magnus force, perfectly vertical fall\par
{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}Uniform gravitational acceleration; implies constant acceleration\par

\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 In reality not a single one of these is true, but we ignore them all since they typically make insignifcant changes to our answer.\par
However, in this example, one of these in particular may indeed be of significance: air resistance, also known as aerodynamic drag. If the ball in question is large, filled with air, or oddly shaped, the air resistance acting on it may in fact become comparable to its weight, and in the limit, cause the ball to reach a terminal velocity. This is in direct violation of our simple model, which states the ball's speed should keep increasing as it falls.\par
\par
\par
\b Incorporating air resistance into the problem\b0\par
Air resistance is caused by friction between a moving object and the air molecules surrounding it\super [3]\nosupersub . The energy required to push these molecules out of the way is taken from its kinetic energy store, therefore reducing its speed.\par
The drag equation quantifies exactly how much drag affects an object. Drag is modelled as being proportional to speed squared, acting in the direction against the object's velocity with magnitude\par
